    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4ee0adc47e9562db",
      "text": "This way of perceiving ICTs assumes that the functionality provided by technology is established and cannot be changed. This creates the problem identified by Rushkoff (2010) where \"instead of optimizing our machines for humanity – or even the benefit of some particular group – we are optimizing humans for machinery\" (p. 15). Perhaps in no small way the established view of ICT in e-learning contributes to Dede’s (2008) observation that \"widely used instructional technology applications have less variety in approach than a low-end fast-food restaurant\" (p. 58)."
